### 37.

1\. Now at the time when the venerable Kassapa of Uruve*l*a went forth
(from the world), much property in brass and wood and earthenware came
into the possession of the Sa*m*gha <span
id="fr_427"></span>[2](#fn_419.md). And the

<span id="page_156">p. 156</span>

<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span> Bhikkhus thought,
'What kinds of brass ware--of wooden things--of earthenware <span
id="fr_428"></span>[1](#fn_420.md)--has the Blessed One allowed, and what
kinds has he not allowed?'

They told this matter to the Blessed One.

Then the Blessed One, on that occasion and in that connection, when he
had delivered a religious discourse, addressed the Bhikkhus, and said:

'I allow you, O Bhikkhus, all kinds of brass ware, except weapons <span
id="fr_429"></span>[2](#fn_421.md)--all kinds of wooden things, except
divans <span id="fr_430"></span>[3](#fn_422.md), and long-armed
chairs <span id="fr_431"></span>[3](#fn_422.md), and bowls <span
id="fr_432"></span>[4](#fn_423.md), and shoes <span
id="fr_433"></span>[5](#fn_424.md),--and all kinds of earthenware, except
katakas <span id="fr_434"></span>[6](#fn_425.md), and large earthen vessels
to be used as huts to live in  <span id="fr_435"></span>[7](#fn_426.md).'

=====================

Here ends the Fifth Khandhaka, on minor details.

 

